# **Part 2**

## **Describe a time when you received a message or email and it took you a long time to reply.**

One experience that immediately comes to mind happened about a year ago when I received a very long email from one of my high school friends who was studying abroad in Canada. We hadn’t talked to each other for several months, so I was quite surprised when I suddenly saw his email appear in my inbox late at night.

The email itself was quite emotional and personal. He talked about the pressure of studying overseas, difficulties adapting to a new environment, and even some conflicts he had with his roommates. Besides that, he also asked me for advice about whether he should continue studying there or return to China. It wasn’t the kind of message that I could reply to casually in just a few minutes.

The main reason it took me such a long time to respond was that I wanted to be careful with my words. I knew he was going through a difficult period emotionally, so I didn’t want to give him a superficial reply like “Don’t worry” or “Everything will be fine.” Instead, I spent quite a lot of time thinking about what I would say. I even wrote several drafts before finally sending the email. In total, it probably took me two or three days to reply properly.

In my response, I tried to encourage him and remind him why he originally chose to study abroad. I also shared some of my own experiences about stress and uncertainty as a university student. More importantly, I wanted him to feel supported rather than judged.

Honestly speaking, the experience made me realize that replying to messages is not only about speed. Sometimes a thoughtful response is much more valuable than an immediate one. After receiving my email, he thanked me and said my advice really helped him calm down. That made me feel very relieved and happy because I felt that our friendship had become even stronger.

---

## **中文翻译：**

我立刻想到的一次经历发生在大约一年前。当时我收到了一封来自高中朋友的长邮件，他当时正在加拿大留学。我们已经好几个月没有联系了，所以那天晚上突然在邮箱里看到他的邮件时，我还挺惊讶的。

那封邮件内容其实非常感性，也很私人。他谈到了海外学习的压力、适应新环境的困难，甚至还提到了和室友之间的一些矛盾。除此之外，他还问我，自己是否应该继续留在国外学习，还是回国。显然，这并不是那种几分钟就能随便回复的信息。

我之所以花了很长时间回复，主要是因为我想认真措辞。我知道他当时情绪状态不太好，所以我不想只是简单说一句“别担心”或者“都会好的”。相反，我花了很多时间思考该怎么表达。我甚至写了好几个草稿，最后才把邮件发出去。总共大概花了两三天才正式回复。

在回复中，我尽量鼓励他，并提醒他当初为什么选择出国留学。我还分享了一些自己作为大学生面对压力和迷茫时的经历。更重要的是，我希望他能感受到支持，而不是被评判。

老实说，这次经历让我意识到，回复消息并不仅仅是拼速度。有时候，一个认真、真诚的回复比立刻回复更加重要。在收到我的邮件之后，他特意感谢了我，并说我的建议确实让他冷静了很多。我当时特别欣慰，也觉得我们的友谊变得更深了。

